post_text:
Good afternoon,

We are so excited about school starting tomorrow. Please remember that our health and safety depends on families and parents being honest and keeping their kiddos home if they have fever or are sick. Also, you are required to report to the school if your student has Covid 19. There is a list of three requirements that will allow your child to come back to school. For detailed information, review our reopening plan on the district website. We want to be able to stay in school, and you can help us make that happen!

See you tomorrow!

Message from Dr. Ray DeSpain, Superintendent of Irion County ISD:

Governor Abbot has just announced that Texas Public Schools are to be closed for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. The Commissioner of Education will be forwarding details to Superintendents next week regarding continued Distance Learning and alternative means of Education, Grading, Graduations, End of Year Events, and other specifics. Thank you and have a blessed day.

Attention all 8th-12th students and parents:

I would like to clear up some confusion I created with regard to email addresses and Zoom meetings.

Monday, March 23rd will be to make sure that all 8th -12 students have access to their Irion-isd.org email addresses.

Each student will receive an email from me before 4PM on Monday, March 23rd which they will be expected to respond.

Zoom Meetings will begin on Tuesday, March 24th and each grade level will be emailed their meeting URL and instructions to download zoom to their Irion-isd.org email before 6PM Monday, March 23rd.

I hope this clears up any confusion. If there are any questions, please do not hesitate to call the HS office in the morning beginning at 9 AM. 325-835-2881

Thank you,

Ms. Chapman

Phone Message from Ms. Chapman to All 9th-12th Students & Parents. Sent @ 3:00 PM March 18th

Good Afternoon, this is Shannon Chapman, secondary principal. This message is attended for all 9th-12th students and parents. At this time, I would like to ascertain the at home internet capabilities of all ICHS 9th- 12th students in order to facilitate the online educational services that will begin on Monday, March 23rd. I am asking that any student that does not have access to the internet at home please call the High School office by 12 PM on Thursday, March 19th and speak with Ms. Whitlow, Ms. Rutherford, or myself.

Thank you,

Ms. Chapman

post_text:
This is Brian Gray, Superintendent of Irion County ISD. Out of an abundance of caution and due to poor travel conditions and multiple flooded and washed out areas within our district....we are cancelling school today, Wednesday, May 8th. Safety is our priority and we do not want buses, students and parents to travel in these conditions.

School will resume tomorrow, Thursday, May 9th at normal time. If there is any change we will disseminate that information.

The End of Course/STAAR Biology Exam will take place tomorrow as well for those HS kids.

Please note that we will still be out of school on Friday as scheduled on the calendar as we have enough minutes that we will not be required to make today up.

Once again, due to safety concerns, school is cancelled today. Thank you for your continued support of IC ISD. Go Hornets!

Attention All Parents & Students:

2019-2020 Physical information

Shannon Sports Medicine will provide free physicals this Wednesday for any Irion County student that needs one.

Buses will be leaving at 1:10 to take students to San Angelo for this free service.

The following students MUST get physicals before participating in cheer, athletics, or marching band (8-12) next year:



ATHLETICS

· ALL current 6th, 7th, 8th, and 10th graders participating next year

· ANY athlete that had a major injury this year

MARCHING BAND

· ALL current 7th, 8th, 10th graders

· ANY marching band member that does not have one

CHEER

· ANY cheerleader that doesn’t fit into a category listed above



If you have any questions, please contact Coach Conner or Mr. Tillman.

post_text:
Mr. Gonzalez’s Spanish II classes has been studying Dia de los Muertos. Here are their creative alter projects from their studies.

Dia de los Muertos is not the Mexican version of Halloween. Mexicans have celebrated Day of the dead since they year 1800 B.C.
Although its origin is Mexican, it is also celebrated in other spanish speaking countries in central and south America.
Dia de los Muertos is not supposed to be sad or morbid, is a time of remembrance and joy as many families in Latin America honor and remember their loved ones who have passed. Altars are not for worship but for offering our love and remembering our departed family members.
In most places the celebration lasts 3 days, from October 31st - November 2nd.
Feliz Dia de los Muertos!

As we complete yearbook pages, the unpublished photos will be added to the album. Please contact Jaime Cormier at the school with any questions.

Also, be on the lookout for details on an app you can use to upload pictures to the yearbook staff with great pictures you may have!

post_text:
Attention all 7th- 12th grade parents and students: The initial drug test for the 2018-2019 school year will be Thursday, August 2nd @ 11:00 AM in the foyer of the new gym. All 7th-12th grade students participating in any extra-curricular activity or parking a vehicle on campus must complete the initial drug test. Biological consent forms must be signed by both the student and parent in order to test. Forms can be picked up in the HS office, from coaches, or downloaded from the school website. Please be advised that School Board Policy states students may not participate in any contest or park on campus until the first initial test is completed. There will be a second test date after school begins. Please call the HS office if you have questions or concerns.

6th grade boys playing football will need to fill out forms as well.

Physicals were completed at the end of the school year.

post_text:
Today are Seniors & Juniors took a field trip to the Angelo State University library to tour the Porter Henderson Library and to also view the Remnant Trust Rare Book Exhibit. Students were able to view the following: books and manuscripts dating back as far as the 13th century and written by several of the Founding Fathers, as well as renowned philosophers, entrepreneurs, explorers, social activists, authors, poets and scientists, including:

Confucius, Friedrich Nietzsche and Thomas Aquinas
Aristotle, Nicolai Copernicus and Galileo
Hippocrates, Euclid and Sir Isaac Newton
John Adams, Benjamin Franklin, Thomas Jefferson and Abraham Lincoln
Thomas Paine, Booker T. Washington, Frederick Douglas and Susan B. Anthony
Homer, Voltaire and Ralph Waldo Emerson
Davy Crockett, Sir Walter Raleigh and Machiavelli
Karl Marx, Andrew Carnegie, Adam Smith and many others

Special thank you to ICHS Teacher Alum, Friend of the Porter Henderson Library, and Irion County Resident, Mrs. Debbie McCullough.

post_text: Attention all 7th- 12th grade parents and students: The initial drug test for the 2017-2018 school year will be Thursday, August 3rd @ 10:00 AM in the foyer of the new gym. All 7th-12th grade students participating in any extra-curricular activity or parking a vehicle on campus must complete the initial drug test. Biological consent forms must be signed by both the student and parent in order to test. Forms can be picked up in the HS office, from coaches, or downloaded from the school website. Please be advised that School Board Policy states students may not participate in any contest or park on campus until the first initial test is completed. There will be a second test date after school begins. Please call the HS office if you have questions or concerns.

Congratulations to the Hornet Powerlifting Team. 3rd place Regional Team..
